    (ii) Process piping releases from failures at flanges, joints, welds, valves and valve seals, and drains or bleeds; 
    (iii)Process vessel or pump releases due to cracks, seal failure, or drain, bleed, or plug failure; 
    (iv) Vessel overfilling and spill, or overpressurization and venting through relief valves or rupture disks; and 
    (v)  Shipping container mishandling and breakage or puncturing leading to a spill. 

Upon consideration of the credible releases, a shipping container mishandling scenario was selected for the 500 Area Propellant Storage and Distribution covered process. 

The Alternative Release Scenario chosen involves one full 55-gallon drum of MMH being transported from the 500 Area Interim Storage Area to the 400 Test Area.  While a forklift is loading the 55-gallon drum of MMH onto the transport trailer, there is an accident (another forklift collides with the forklift transporting the drum) that causes the drum to be physically dropped off the transport vehicle, resulting in a rupture of the drum and a release from the 55-gallon drum.  Since a continuous release toxic model was selected, the inputs used were a release rate of 25 pounds per minute and a release duration of 15 minutes.  The response by the on-site Fire Department was estimated to be 15 minutes, which includes curtailment of the release from the drum.  

The Alternative Release Scenario is a liquid release of 100 % MMH, which is identified as a toxic liquid.   The postulated release resulted in 51.13 gallons (375 lbs) of MMH being released at ground level onto an unconfined soil area (not diked).  Upon release of the MMH onto the unconfined soil area, there was subsequent vaporization of MMH into the air.

Meteorological conditions used for the Alternative Release scenario were those selected as representative based on data from the WSTF Facility Master Plan.
